# CaptureAction.action
#
# Models the original system's start_capture / stop_capture mission commands
# as a ROS2 action:
#
#   - Goal:    start capturing at a given interval (mirrors start_capture +
#              interval_s from the original RemoteMissionService)
#   - Feedback: frames captured so far, so callers can monitor progress
#   - Result:   total frames captured when stop is requested or goal completes
#
# Why an action rather than a service?
#   A service call blocks until it returns. start_capture is long-running --
#   you send it and capture keeps going until you cancel or the duration
#   expires. Actions support goal/cancel/feedback/result natively, which
#   is exactly that pattern. This is a common ROS2 design interview question.

# --- Goal (sent by the client to start capture) ---
# Per-camera capture interval in seconds, clamped [0.05, 5.0]
# Matches interval_s in the RemoteMissionService parameter spec.
float32 interval_s
# Maximum capture duration in seconds. 0.0 means run until cancelled.
float32 duration_s
---

# --- Result (returned when action completes or is cancelled) ---
# Total number of frames captured across all active camera nodes
uint64 total_frames
# True if capture was stopped by a cancel request (vs. duration expiry)
bool cancelled
---

# --- Feedback (published periodically while capture is running) ---
# Frames captured so far
uint64 frames_so_far
# Elapsed time since capture started, in seconds
float32 elapsed_s
